---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Aside from '../../../components/Aside.astro';
import {funktorSidebar} from '../../../data/funktor-sidebar';
import {Code} from 'astro:components';
---

<DocsLayout title="Logging Module" sidebar={funktorSidebar} description="Structured logging with database persistence">

    <h1>Logging</h1>

    <p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
        Structured logging with database persistence, filtering, and a web UI.
    </p>

    <h2>How it works</h2>

    <p>The logging module provides a Logback appender that persists log entries to your database.
        Entries are searchable, filterable, and viewable through a built-in web UI.</p>

    <h2>Setting up the appender</h2>

    <p>Add the database log appender in your Ktor application module. It captures Logback events
        at or above the specified level and writes them to the configured storage backend.</p>

    <Code code={`fun Application.module() = app.module(this) { app, config, init ->
    // Persist log entries at INFO level and above to ArangoDB
    addKarangoAppender(config = config.arangodb, minLevel = Level.INFO)

    // ... rest of your server setup
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Choosing a storage backend</h2>

    <p>Configure the storage backend in your Kontainer blueprint. The logging module supports
        ArangoDB and MongoDB out of the box.</p>

    <Code code={`val blueprint = kontainer {
    funktor(
        config = config,
        logging = {
            useKarango()   // ArangoDB via Karango
            // or
            // useMonko()  // MongoDB via Monko
        },
        // ... other modules
    )
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Features</h2>

    <div class="not-prose grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-8">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02]">
            <h3 class="text-white font-semibold mb-1">Database-backed</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Log entries stored in ArangoDB or MongoDB. Survives
                restarts. Searchable by level, logger, message, and timestamp.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02]">
            <h3 class="text-white font-semibold mb-1">Web UI</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Browse, search, and filter logs from the admin panel.
                Pre-built <a href="/ultra/kraft/" class="text-brand-400">Kraft</a> components for
                log list and detail views.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02]">
            <h3 class="text-white font-semibold mb-1">Bulk actions</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Acknowledge, archive, or delete log entries in batch
                through the web UI or REST API.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02]">
            <h3 class="text-white font-semibold mb-1">REST API</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Query logs programmatically via <code>LoggingApiClient</code>.
                Filter by severity, date range, or search text.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <Aside>The appender hooks into Logback, so any library that logs through SLF4J
        automatically gets its entries persisted. No code changes needed in your application logic.
    </Aside>

    <div class="mt-12">
        <a href="/ultra/funktor/staticweb"
           class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 rounded-lg bg-brand-400/10 text-brand-400 border border-brand-400/30 hover:bg-brand-400/20 transition-all font-medium">
            Static Web Module &rarr;
        </a>
    </div>

</DocsLayout>
